1

Abstract

2

Food delivery is becoming a new popular food trend in China, and the food delivery market has

3

great potential for development in China. Therefore, this project aims to build an Intelligent

4

online food delivery website with Python, Django, and MySQL. For customers, it has features like registration, address management, favorites, shopping carts, and the ability to review and

5

rate purchases. For shop owners, the website offers features to manage their store and

6

products, as well as order management features. In addition to this, the website uses a Hybrid

7

Recommendation System to provide personalized recommendations to the users by using User-

8

based Collaborative Filtering (User-CF) technology along with Content-Based Filtering (CB) technology to analyze the user's preferences as well as the similarity of the product.

9

This approach not only enhances the shopping experience but also boosts sales by intelligently

10

matching products with customers' preferences. The integration of multiple recommendation

11

algorithms has established the food delivery website as a leading choice for customers seeking

12

a personalized shopping experience and for store owners seeking to enhance their exposure through the platform.

13

Keywords: Recommendation system, Hybrid recommendation, Collaborative filtering,

14

Content-based filtering, User-CF, Food delivery

15

Abbreviations

16

CF: Collaborative Filtering

17

User-CF: User-based collaborative filtering

18

Item-CF: Item-based collaborative filtering

19

RS: Recommendation system

20

CB: Content-based filtering

21

Glossary

22

Recommendation System:

23

A Recommendation system is an information filtering system that provides personalized item

24

recommendations to users in specific scenarios based on user or item data.[1]

25

Hybrid recommendation:

26

A hybrid recommendation system is a method that combines multiple recommendation

27

techniques to address the shortcomings of individual models. The integration of multiple

28

recommendation algorithms enables the generation of more accurate recommendations that overcome the limitations inherent in a single recommendation algorithm.[2].

29

Content-based filtering:

30

By analyzing the features of products that target users are interested in, content-based filtering methods recommend similar products to users [3].

31

Collaborative Filtering:

32

User-based Collaborative Filtering algorithms will recommend items of interest to the user based on the calculation of user or item similarity [4]. There are two common collaborative filtering methods: User collaborative filtering and Item-based collaborative filtering [5].

33

User-based Collaborative Filtering:

34

Is an algorithm in collaborative filtering algorithm, which recommends items or product that similar users like for users by finding similar users for them.

35

Cosine Similarity:

36

Cosine similarity is a commonly used measure in computer science to determine the similarity

37

between two vectors. It helps determine the relationship between two related items, making it a

38

common method for assessing the similarity of users or items based on their features or behaviors [6][7].

39

Jaccard Index:

40

The Jaccard index is a statistical measure used to compare the similarity and diversity of

41

sample sets. In recommendation systems, this index is used to compare users or items based on their ratings, thus helping to identify similar users or items with common appeal [8].

42

Cold start:

43

The Cold Start refers to the difficulty of generating accurate recommendations when a

44

recommendation system is just getting started, due to a lack of sufficient user behavioral data or item data.

45

Django:

46

Django is a Python web framework that provides a set of methods to help developers to develop and maintain websites [9].

47

Chapter 1 Introduction

48

1.1 Background

49

In the era of highly developed information technology and logistics industry, online take-out has

50

become a new trend sweeping the world, especially in China, ordering take-out has become a new popular way of eating in China [10][11].

51

However, the increasing health consciousness of customers and their growing demand for

52

healthy food options has become a major trend in the online food delivery market. As a result,

53

online food delivery platforms need to respond by offering a wider range of healthy and

54

sustainable food choices. In addition to this, online food delivery platforms have been suffering

55

from reduced information utilization and "information overload", where too many product categories can make it difficult for users to find their favorite information. Over time, users become less interested in the platform [10][12].

56

To solve this problem, the use of recommendation systems has become an effective technical

57

choice [10]. Therefore, in this project, a hybrid recommendation system is implemented in which

58

the User-CF algorithm is integrated with the CB algorithm to provide personalized

59

recommendations of products to the customers through an intelligent recommendation system

60

to reduce the information overload problem faced by the users. Integrating these two

61

recommendation methods is expected to provide users with more accurate and personalized recommendation services [2].

62

1.2 Aim

63

The main goal of this project is to integrate a User-CF algorithm and CB into a hybrid

64

recommendation system, so as to improve the user experience of the ordering platform by providing highly personalized and targeted food recommendations.

65

1.3 Objectives

66

The object are as follows:

67

1. Research on the Existing Food Delivery Platform

68

2. Comparison between food delivery platforms

69

3. Research on recommendation system

70

4. Research on CF and CB

71

5. Function requirements analysis

72

6. System design (divided into several modules)

73

7. Web Implementation (Implement the front-end and back-end)

74

8. Recommend function design 9. Develop recommend function

75

10. Test and evaluate website function

76

11. System testing & performance analysis

77

1.4 Project Overview

78

1.4.1 Scope

79

The project aims to develop an intelligent recommendation system for an online food ordering

80

platform. The objective is to enhance the user experience by providing personalized food

81

recommendations. The website caters to two main types of users: customers and merchants.

82

For customers, the website will offer features: registration, address management, My favorites,

83

shopping cart management, order management and viewing order status, payment features

84

with the option to cancel payments, as well as the ability to post comments and rate stores and

85

products after purchase. Additionally, users will be able to manage orders and search for

86

products or stores. The recommendation system will employ a hybrid recommendation system

87

for logged-in customers with substantial order history, providing tailor-made suggestions by analyzing the preferences of similar users.

88

On the merchant side, the platform will allow for account and store registration, product management, and order management along with access to store performance data.

89

The integration of this hybrid recommendation system with the online ordering platform will

90

markedly enhance the user experience. By analyzing and utilizing user data and preferences,

91

the platform is designed to enhance customer satisfaction, while increasing exposure and sales for merchant stores.

92

1.4.2 Audience

93

The primary audience of our platform includes the following:

94

1. For customers who are looking for a personalized, recommended ordering experience, the

95

website's recommendation system can efficiently and accurately recommend foods they may be interested in to meet their individual dietary needs.

96

2. The website provides merchants with the opportunity to showcase their products and personalize product recommendations for each customer by using the power of user data and preferences, greatly increasing their chances of increasing sales.

97

3. For those with limited time and energy, our platform is a more convenient and intelligent

98

solution. The site is able to provide users with fast, personalized meal recommendations based on their data and historical behavior.

99

Chapter 2 Background Review

100

2.1 Existing approach of Recommendation system:

101

In this section, we will discuss and review the existing approach to recommendation systems.

102

Faced with the problem of information overload caused by the rapid development of the Internet. Therefore, recommendation systems are designed to solve this problem [13].

103

Recommendation systems are information filtering systems providing a personalized item

104

recommendation to a user in a service environment that can hold or collect various data [1]. In

105

fact, Recommendation systems are widely used in various fields, such as e-commerce and food

106

delivery recommendation, which not only brings benefits to the merchant but also bring convenience to the users [10].

107

The current mainstream approaches to recommendation systems are illustrated in Figure 1.

108

This figure outlines the hierarchy of mainstream sub-models of current recommendation system models into three main approaches: CB (using item features for recommendation), collaborative

109

filtering and hybrid systems. Collaborative filtering methods are categorized into model-based

110

and memory-based approaches based on the way they process the rating data of users and

111

items [1]. Furthermore, memory-based collaborative filtering can be subdivided into two categories: User-CF and Item-CF [14].

112

Figure 1: Overview of recommendation models [1].

113

2.1.1 CB (Content-based filtering)

114

CB is an algorithm that recommend items to users based on the features of the items and the user's preferences. For example, recommending products to users based on their information

115

about the product itself of interest [3]. For the CB recommendation algorithm, it is characterized by its ability to accurately extract the user's interests and does not require data from other users [14].

116

Figure 2 below outlines the principles of CB models in recommendation systems. As an

117

example, it shows that for different users, in a collection of food items, these items are

118

associated with personalized user preference data, indicating that user A likes strawberries and

119

user B likes pancakes. By using recommendation techniques to analyze the content of the

120

items, recommendations can be obtained for specific categories, such as "fruit" for User A and "bread" for User B.

121

Figure 2: Recommendation principle of Contents-Based Filtering Model [1].

122

2.1.2 User CF (User-based collaborative filtering)

123

User-CF is based on calculating the similarity between users and then recommending products

124

that are liked by other users similar to the target user [3]. For calculating similarity, cosine

125

similarity is usually used to determine the similarity between users. In online delivery website can recommend similar item based on similar tastes between similar users [5][10].

126

User-CF is characterized by high accuracy without extracting the item's features and with a

127

complete and rich dataset. In addition, User-CF can extract some potential correlations between recommended items and user preferences [14].

128

2.1.3 Limitation of Collaborative filter and Content-based filtering:

129

 Limitation of User-CF:

130

Firstly, Li and Wang [14] discuss that as the number of users in the system increases, User-CF

131

is confronted with the challenge of maintaining a large user similarity matrix. This not only

132

increases the time required for recommendation computation but also reduces the system's

133

overall efficiency. Furthermore, User-CF does not involve the mining of item content, and therefore cannot address the cold-start problem for new items.

134

Second, Cacheda et al. [4] note that although User-CF is relatively simple to implement and provides fairly accurate results, it suffers from serious scalability problems. In order to make

135

recommendations, the algorithm must process all the stored data, which is not feasible for large-scale online systems that require real-time recommendations.

136

Furthermore, Huang, Chen, and Zeng [15] highlight that since users typically rate only a few

137

items and the majority of item data remains unrated, the challenge of recommending product

138

diversity in this context is significant. Additionally, there is a paucity of behavioral history for new users to analyze, which further complicates the task of providing recommendations.

139

Consequently, User-CF also encounters limitations such as the sparsity of the rating matrix and the cold-start problem.

140

 Limitation of CB:

141

Li and Wang [14] points out that CB may ignore objects that the user has not been exposed to

142

before due to over-inclusion during the recommendation process. This situation can lead to monotony in the recommended content, depriving the user of the opportunity to explore new types of information, and thus a lack of novelty.

143

In addition, Cacheda et al. [4] explain that CB requires ITEMS that can be parsed by machine,

144

which poses difficulties for the processing of multimedia information, because machine

145

perception of content is different from human perception. Although manually labeled multimedia

146

content solves this problem to some extent, CB still struggles to handle the vast amount of

147

information available today. In addition, CB also can’t discover items that appear irrelevant but are actually interesting to the user's profile, it lacks the ability to make unexpected discoveries.

148

Finally, Salter and Antonopoulos [16] CB model only recommends data that is closely related to items that the user has previously evaluated, thus failing to provide access to diverse content. This suggests a clear limitation in the system's ability to recommend new items, thus reducing the user's exposure to new content.

149

 Conclusion:

150

Obviously, both User-CF and CB Recommendation have limitations, especially under conditions

151

of data sparsity, which can lead to the cold start problem - difficulty in making accurate recommendations for new users or items without sufficient data [4].

152

2.1.4 Hybrid recommendation system:

153

To address these challenges, hybrid recommendation systems have emerged. A hybrid

154

recommendation system is an approach that combines multiple recommendation techniques,

155

which mitigates the shortcomings of a single model by integrating multiple recommendation models. This approach enables websites to provide more accurate recommendations, even when faced with the typical cold-start problems associated with new items or users [10].

156

Bondevik et al. [17] describe a hybrid system that utilizes different data sources to enhance the precision and personalization of recommendations provided to users. This system represents a

157

significant advancement in addressing the inherent limitations of traditional recommendation models, thereby markedly increasing user satisfaction and engagement on the platform.

158

Song et al.[18] states that a hybrid recommendation method that combines a weighted

159

combination of User-CF and CB methods based on existing models is able to capture user evaluations of food more accurately than a single traditional recommendation technique. A

160

hybrid approach to recommendation methods was found to be more accurate than traditional

161

methods in identifying user preferences for different food products and in considering similarities between users and food products. This resulted in more accurate recommendations.

162

Pu and Hu [19] selected a hybrid recommendation algorithm for recommending movies in their

163

study. The experimental results show that the hybrid recommendation algorithm achieves an accuracy of 81%, which is better than the traditional CB, Item-CF and User-CF algorithms.

164

Praditya, Permanasari, and Hidayah [20] propose that the limitations of existing models can be

165

overcome by implementing a hybrid approach. The system utilizes three distinct models. A

166

method for recommending travel itineraries to users is developed by combining the User-CF, CB, and K-Nearest Neighbor Algorithms.

167

Shao and Xie [21] designed a hybrid algorithm utilizing user attributes and BP networks to solve

168

the new user problem at cold start. The users are clustered according to their interests, and

169

then the clustering results and the demographic information of the users are used to construct a

170

decision tree, which associates the new users with the existing users, so as to realize the

171

recommendation of new users. Experimental results show that the algorithm can improve the recommendation performance.

172

2.1.5 Item-based popularity recommendation:

173

In addition, based on the discussion of the cold start problem above. In order to solve the cold

174

start problem for new users, this project develops a recommendation function based on the

175

popularity of the item, which is based on the extraction of the metadata of the item itself, and

176

sorts the items according to their popularity, so as to recommend them to new users. This

177

avoids the situation where there is no product to recommend if the new user has no user data to extract.

178

3.1.6 Recommendation system approach:

271

This section shows in detail the composition of the Hybrid recommendation system

272

implemented in the project, the operation flow and the principle of the recommendation algorithm.

273

i. Composition of recommendation system

274

The recommendation system in this project consists of the following three recommendation

275

methodologies, namely User-CF, CB and Item-based popularity recommendation. The composition of these methodologies is illustrated in detail in Figure 9.

276

Figure 9: Composition of hybrid recommendation system.

277

ii. Operation flow of recommendation:

278

Figure 10 depicts the complete operational flow of the recommendation system for making

279

recommendations for a user. The recommended sequence of steps is as follows:

280

 Step 1: Checks if the user is logged in and what type of user they are:

281

This step to verifies the user's login status and user type. Only users who are logged in and whose user type is customer have historical behavioral data that can be utilized to analyze and subsequently personalize the recommendation service for them.

282

 Step 2: Check if the user's historical behavior data is sufficient:

283

This step checks whether the user's historical behavioral data (such as the number of

284

purchase orders and the number of favorite products, etc. ) is sufficiently large, and if it is

285

not sufficiently large, then the use of Item-based popularity recommendation is to avoid the use of Hybrid recommendation to avoid the use of less historical behavioral data to produce

286

a relatively large bias

287

 Step 3: Hybrid recommendation:

288

In this step, the system employs two recommendation algorithms (User-CF and CB) to generate recommendations, which are then merged using a weighting method.

289

 Step 4: Filter out low-rated product:

290

The objective of this step is to filter the items in the generated recommendation results in order to avoid the recommendation results that have items rated as low by users but are still recommended.

291

Figure 10: The operation flow of recommendation.

292

iii. Item-based popularity recommendation:

293

In item-based popularity recommendation, the recommendation score is calculated by extracting

294

the metadata of the item itself. This allows the most popular items to be recommended to the

295

user. In this recommendation function, two operations are used to calculate the score:

296

 Min-Max Scaling Normalize:

297

The formula (1) is used for normalizing data values within a specified range. This transformation

298

redirects the features to a fixed range (0,1), which ensures that each feature has an equal

299

impact on the model, thus avoiding that certain features may have a disproportionate impact on the prediction results due to their large range of values.

300

𝑥=

301

𝑥− min(𝑥)

302

max(𝑥)− min(𝑥)

303

(1)

304

where x represents an original value, min(x) is the minimum value in the data set, max(x) is the maximum value, and x' is the normalized value.

305

 Recommend score:

306

Formula (2) defines how metadata is used in the item-based popularity recommendation

307

function to calculate the recommendation scores of different items according to their weights.

308

𝑅𝑒𝑐𝑜𝑚𝑚𝑒𝑛𝑑𝑆𝑐𝑜𝑟𝑒=

310

The variables are as follows:‘w’ represents weight,‘avgRate’ represents the average rating of

311

the item,‘favorite’ represents the number of favorites, and ‘sales’ represents the total number of sales of the item.

312

After the calculation of (1) and (2) above, the products are sorted in descending order according

313

to the value of the recommendation score. Subsequently, the products with high scores are

314

recommended to the users. The advantage of such an operation is that it does not require the

315

user's historical behavioral data, which effectively solves the cold-start problem of the recommendation system.

316

iv. User-CF:

317

For the implementation of User-CF function, we first create item-user table to store the item and

318

the corresponding user who likes the item, then use Adjusted Cosine Similarity to calculate the similarity between the customer users, build the user similarity matrix, and then recommend the item according to the similar user's favorite item to recommend the item according to the similar user's favorite item.

319

320

As shown in Table 2, the item-user table stores the item id and the corresponding ids of all

321

users interested in the item. the item-user table is implemented to facilitate the later calculation of user similarity and recommendation of items of interest to similar users.

322

 Adjusted Cosine Similarity:

328

Traditional recommendation algorithms frequently rely on explicit user feedback (e. g., ratings or reviews) to form "nearest neighbor sets" that predict user preferences. However, these methods

329

can be influenced by arbitrary ratings or incomplete feedback from users that represent their

330

implicit behavior [27]. Consequently, explicit feedback alone does not fully capture user

331

preferences. To address this issue, we propose replacing the traditional cosine similarity with

332

adjust cosine similarity, a formula that incorporates implicit user feedback to enhance prediction accuracy.

333

As show as in formula (3), Adjusted Cosine Similarity is primarily used in collaborative filtering to measure similarity between two users based on their ratings, adjusting for the average rating of each user to avoid bias from varying user rating scales.

334

𝑆𝑖𝑚(i, j)= 

335

∑ r , − r r , − r ∈  

336

∑ r , − r ∈   ∑ r , − r ∈  

337

  (3)

338

𝑈 denotes the set of users who rated both items 𝑖 and 𝑗. where 𝑟, and 𝑟, are the ratings given

339

by user 𝑢 to items 𝑖 and 𝑗, respectively, and 𝑟¯𝑢 is the average rating of user 𝑢. This metric compensates for user bias, making it effective for personalized recommendations.

340

 User similarity matrix:

341

342

v. Content-based filtering algorithm:

351

In the context of CB, the user's behavior is analyzed in order to identify products that may be of interest to them. Metadata associated with these products is then used to calculate the similarity

352

between them, with the aim of identifying products that the user may be interested in. The

353

feature matrix is employed to record the feature matrix of the products, while the Jaccard index is utilized to calculate the similarity between them.

354

355

The feature matrix for CB is constructed by extracting and combining various item attributes into a structured format. All the features are explained in detail in Table 4.

356

 User preference vector:

371

A user preference vector is a mathematical representation of a user’s preferences, constructed

372

from the aggregation of features of items that the user has interacted with. This vector

373

essentially summarizes the user's tastes and preferences in a form that can be easily compared and analyzed against item features.

374

 Jaccard Index:

375

The Jaccard Index is a statistical measure used to assess the similarity and diversity of sample

376

sets. As shown in formula (4), the similarity between two sets can be quantified by calculating

377

the ratio of the size of the intersection set to the size of the merged set. A larger ratio indicates a greater degree of similarity between the two sets.

378

4.1.2 Functional testing:

797

Functional testing is an important aspect of software development, and such testing evaluates

798

the various functions of a system by inputting and verifying outputs to ensure that the

799

application performs as expected under various conditions. Functional testing not only helps verify the operation of the application, but also helps detect unexpected behavior or errors.

800

During testing, we designed tests that simulate user interactions with the application to validate

801

the functionality of the Web pages. These tests include scenarios such as form submission,

802

user authentication, database interaction, etc. to ensure that all components work according to

803

the defined requirements and behaviors. The test results are shown and explained in detail in Table 8.

4.1.3 Performance testing:

897

Performance testing is an approach to evaluating the responsiveness, stability, and resource consumption of a website under varying load conditions.

898

This performance test was conducted using Locust, an open-source load testing tool designed

899

to simulate the simultaneous operation of users on a website in order to assess the website's

900

performance under high traffic conditions. The testing process is as follows:

901

 The number of virtual users was gradually increased to simulate the access and operation of real users.

902

 Performance testing is a process that involves the evaluation of key performance metrics,

903

such as response time, throughput, and error rate. The following table 9 provides a detailed explanation of each of the performance metrics included in a performance test.

904

Table 9: Performance testing metrics table

905

1. User Load

906

User load refers to the number of concurrent users accessing the system or

907

application at any given time. Performance testing simulates different user loads to assess how the website performs under varying levels of stress.

908

2. Response

909

time

910

Response Time is the time it takes from when a user makes a request to when

911

they receive a response from the system, typically the time it takes for a webpage to complete loading.

912

3. Error rates Failure rates refer to the percentage of requests that fail during performance testing. High failure rates typically indicate system stability issues.

913

4. Response

914

percentile time

915

Response Percentile Time is a method of evaluating the value at which a certain percentage of data points are less than or equal to all observations. This value is

916

often used to eliminate the effects of extreme values and provides a more

917

accurate characterization of system performance under normal conditions.

918

5. Throughput Throughput is the number of requests that a system successfully processes per unit of time.

919

During the test, we recorded the changes in several key performance metrics in relation to the number of test users. The detailed data of the test is shown in Table 9 below.

920

The average response time increases with the number of concurrent users, from 57.4 ms for 70

921

users to 282.4 ms for 500 users, and reaches 1302.3 ms for 500 users after 2 seconds. This shows that the response time of the site is more affected by higher loads.

922

The throughput also generally increases with the number of users, peaking at 175 requests per

923

second at 0.5 seconds after the number of users increases to 500. When the system is tested

924

under heavy load after the peak number of users is reached, the throughput is found to gradually decrease, eventually staying around 141 requests per second.

925

The error rate remained at 0% until the user load reached 500. After that, it increased to 0.93% and then 2.68%.

926

Table 11 shows the performance test cases that are used to simulate real user behavior.

927

Table 11: Request test case table

928

999

In this test, it was observed that significant performance bottlenecks occurred when the number

1,000

of users increased to 500, particularly at the 95th percentile, where the response time

1,001

approached 7 seconds, which greatly exceeded the ideal response time standard. Additionally,

1,002

the server exhibited signs of under-resourcing under high concurrent requests, indicating the need to optimize the server configuration or increase resources to support higher loads.

1,003

Furthermore, the tests identified multiple ConnectionRefusedError errors, indicating a need for further investigation into the network configuration or the server's ability to accept connections.

1,004

It is important to note that while the tests attempt to simulate real user behavior, actual user actions may be more complex and therefore the results may be biased.

1,005

4.1.4 Security testing:

1,006

The primary purpose of website security testing is to identify potential threats that could threaten

1,007

the security, stability, and data integrity of a website. Through these tests, we can prevent unauthorized access and data leakage, and ensure the privacy and information security of website users.

1,008

This security test uses the OWASP ZAP tool, which is used to automatically detect security vulnerabilities in applications.

1,009

The alerts in the report are categorized by risk level, including high, medium, low and

1,010

informational alerts. Table 12 and Table 13 below clearly show the types and number of

1,011

warnings for different risk levels:

1,012

 Medium risk Warnings:3 warnings were identified, primarily related to not configuring CSP and using third-party inventory with vulnerabilities.

1,013

 Low risk warnings:5 warnings have been identified, including improper cookie settings that

1,014

do not use the HttpOnly attribute and error messages that could expose sensitive information.

1,015

 Informational Alerts:6 items, such as URLs that contain sensitive information.

1,016

Table 12: Alert risk level count table

1,017

Alert risk level High Medium Low Alert Number of alerts 0356

1,018

Table 13: Alert risk type and count table

1,019

Alert type

1,020

Risk

1,021

Level

1,022

Count

1,023

1,024

1,025

1,026

1,037

While most of the medium risks have been successfully identified, the report also notes the

1,038

existence of unresolved issues, particularly vulnerabilities in some third-party libraries, which

1,039

may require more sophisticated update strategies and compatibility testing. In addition, while the

1,040

low risks in the report do not currently pose an immediate threat, the security posture may

1,041

gradually weaken if they are ignored over time. Meanwhile, testing limitations to be aware of include the limitations of automated tools, which may generate false positives or miss reports when dealing with customized content and complex user interactions.

1,042

5.3 Professional Issues

1,421

5.3.1 Legal Issues

1,422

 Identification:

1,423

Comply with privacy laws regarding the collection and security of user information. Verifying merchants and products to prevent fraudulent activity.

1,424

 Discussion:

1,425

In order to comply with the ethical principles of the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM), it is essential to implement secure data management practices, such as encrypted storage and secure transmission protocols [28]. These practices serve to protect data integrity and ensure that user data privacy is respected. Moreover, websites are required to inform users of the purpose for which their data is being collected. Consequently, websites are required to conduct regular audits and compliance checks in order to ensure compliance with legal standards and ethical principles.

1,426

5.3.2 Social Issues

1,427

 Identification:

1,428

Content Management of Images and Comments: Ensure content is appropriate and free of

1,429

offensive or discriminatory remarks

1,430

Food Diversity: Provide food choices from a variety of cultures and diets.

1,431

 Discussion:

1,432

The ACM Code encourages professionals to be inclusive and respectful of all users, as demonstrated by the management of diverse food products and the vigilant management of user interactions and published content on websites. This includes implementing algorithms and human oversight to ensure that user-generated content (e. g., comments or images) does not violate norms of respect and civility.

1,433

5.3.3 Ethical Issues

1,434

 Identification:

1,435

Clearly display all costs associated with orders on the website

1,436

 Discussion:

1,437

Fee clarity is essential to ensure trust and fairness. This can be achieved by clearly indicating and communicating any fees, taxes or additional charges that may apply to transactions on the platform.

1,438

5.3.4 Environmental Issues

1,439

 Identification:

1,440

Promote consumer education on environmental conservation.

1,441

Implement sustainable, environmentally friendly packaging and delivery materials. Offer customers the option to use their own reusable utensils.

1,442

 Discussion:

1,443

It is recommended that websites serve as a platform to educate consumers on how to reduce their environmental impact. This can be achieved by providing information on sustainable practices and the benefits of reducing single-use plastics. Furthermore, websites should actively promote and utilize environmentally friendly packaging and utensils for food delivery. A shift towards more sustainable consumption habits can be encouraged through the facilitation of customers' choice of reusable tableware or the option of bringing their own.

1,444

This strategic approach not only aligns with ethical guidelines to promote environmental sustainability, but also engages consumers in active participation, fostering a community committed to environmental responsibility.

1,445

Chapter 6 Conclusion

1,446

This project implemented a hybrid recommendation system for an online food delivery website.

1,447

The system utilizes a hybrid of User-CF and CB techniques to provide personalized product recommendations to the website's users.

1,448

 Achievements:

1,449

The integration of User-CF and CB into a hybrid recommendation system allowed for more accurate and personalized recommendations, significantly improving the user experience.

1,450

The website is implemented by using the Django framework and MySQL database, and also

1,451

uses third-party libraries such as Pandas, NumPy, and scikit-learn to process and analyze user data.

1,452

A multitude of testing methodologies were employed to assess the security, reliability,

1,453

scalability, and performance of the website. These methodologies included performance testing,

1,454

security testing, unit testing, and functional testing, which were conducted in a diverse array of scenarios using a range of testing tools.

1,455

 Potential Future Work:

1,456

Future work to further develop the website project can be classified in the following directions:

1,457

Recommendation algorithm improvements: Future work will focus on improving the

1,458

recommendation function by integrating more advanced machine learning models to overcome cold start problems.

1,459

Extending website functionality: For the order functionality, real-time order tracking can be

1,460

added to the website. More advanced search filters can also be added to allow users to more accurately target stores, further increasing user engagement and satisfaction.

1,461
